# Markus

Write research papers, notes, todos, lecture handouts, letters and notices in a **Markdown-like** syntax (`.mks`), compile to **LaTeX-quality PDF**.

```bash
pip install -e .
markus init my-paper
markus build my-paper.mks
```

Requires [TeX Live](https://www.tug.org/texlive/) or [MacTeX](https://www.tug.org/mactex/) with `latexmk` on your `PATH`.

## Quick example

**`paper.mks`**

```markdown
---
title: "My Paper"
author:
  - name: Jane Doe
    affiliation: MIT
template: article
bib: refs.bib
---

# Introduction {#sec:intro}

Inline math $E=mc^2$ and [@smith2020]. See @sec:intro.

$$
\int_0^1 x^2\,dx = \frac{1}{3}
$$ {#eq:integral}
```

```bash
markus build paper.mks
# → paper.tex, paper.pdf
```

## Syntax reference

| Feature | Markus | LaTeX output |
|---------|--------|--------------|
| Section | `# Title {#sec:id}` | `\section` + `\label{sec:id}` |
| Bold / italic | `**b**` / `*i*` | `\textbf` / `\textit` |
| Strikethrough | `~~old~~` | `\sout{old}` |
| Inline math | `$...$` | `$...$` |
| Display math | `$$...$$ {#eq:id}` (label same line or next) | `equation` + `\label` |
| Multi-line math | `$$ a &= b \\ c &= d $$` | `align` (or `gather` without `&`) |
| Citation | `[@key]`, `[@a; @b]`, or bare `@key` | `\cite{key}`, `\cite{a,b}` |
| Reference | `@fig:id`, `@eq:id`, `@sec:id`, `@tbl:id` | `\ref` / `\eqref` |
| Footnote | `text[^1]` then `[^1]: note` | `\footnote{note}` |
| Figure | `![cap](path){#fig:id width=0.8}` | `figure` + `\includegraphics` |
| Task list | `- [ ] todo` / `- [x] done` | checkbox items |
| Nested list | indent 2 spaces | nested `itemize`/`enumerate` |
| Blockquote | `> quoted` | `quote` environment |
| Theorem etc. | `::: theorem Title` ... `:::` | `theorem`, `lemma`, `definition`, `corollary`, ... |
| Callout | `::: warning` ... `:::` | boxed note (`note`, `tip`, `warning`, `important`, ...) |
| Horizontal rule | `---` on its own line | thin rule |
| Page break | `\newpage` on its own line | `\newpage` |
| Comment | `<!-- hidden -->` | removed |
| Hard line break | end a line with `\\` or two spaces | `\\` |
| Escapes | `\$ \* \_ \# \@ \~ \[ \]` | literal characters |
| Raw LaTeX | ` ```latex ` ... ` ``` ` | pasted verbatim |
| Table | GitHub-style `\|...\|` with `:--:` alignment + caption line | `booktabs` table |

Inline markup and math work **everywhere**: titles, headings, captions, and table cells.
Dollar amounts (`$4,500 and $300`), email addresses, and `@` in prose are left alone.
Smart quotes and common Unicode (`→ ✓ ± ≤ α …`) are converted to proper LaTeX automatically.

### Front matter (YAML)

```yaml
---
title: "Paper title"
author: "Name"           # or list of names / {name, affiliation, email}
date: June 12, 2026      # optional, defaults to today
abstract: |
  Multi-line abstract.
keywords: latex, markdown
template: article        # see `markus templates`
bib: refs.bib            # bibliography file
---
```

Tip: in YAML double-quoted strings a backslash is an escape character — use single
quotes for LaTeX in titles: `title: 'A $O(n \log n)$ Study'`.

### Templates

`markus templates` lists all of them:

- **article**, **twocolumn**, **notes** (no title page; tables/figures stay inline)
- **report** (`#` headings become chapters), **assignment** (course/due-date header), **cv**
- **letter** — front matter `to:`, `from:`, `date:`, `subject:`; single newlines are kept as line breaks
- **beamer** — `##` headings start new slides
- venue styles: **ieee**, **ieee-journal**, **ieee-trans**, **acm**, **acm-acmlarge**, **springer**, **nature**, **revtex**, **apa**

**Letter example**

```markdown
---
template: letter
date: June 12, 2026
to: |
  The Registrar
  Stanford University
from: Vishesh Yadav
subject: Fee waiver request
---

Dear Sir/Madam,

I am writing to request a waiver of the $250 late fee.

Sincerely,
Vishesh
```

## CLI

```bash
markus init [name]          # create starter .mks + refs.bib
markus build paper.mks      # .mks → .tex → .pdf
markus build paper.mks -w   # rebuild on every save (watch mode)
markus build paper.mks --tex-only
markus check paper.mks      # lint: unknown refs/citations, missing figures, bad glyphs
markus clean paper.mks      # remove LaTeX build artifacts
markus compile-tex paper.tex
```

`markus build` warns about unknown citation keys, references to missing labels,
missing figure files and characters pdflatex cannot typeset — with `.mks` line numbers.
LaTeX failures report the actual error instead of a half-built PDF; auxiliary files
go to a `.markus-aux/` directory.

## Project layout

```
src/markus/            # compiler (parser, LaTeX emitter, diagnostics, CLI)
src/markus/templates/  # LaTeX skeletons
examples/              # quickstart, formal papers, informal notes (see examples/README.md)
tests/
```

## Editor: `.mks` support (Cursor / VS Code)

A small extension in `vscode-markus/` provides syntax highlighting, file icons,
and a live PDF preview.

Install once (from repo root):

```bash
cursor --install-extension ./vscode-markus
# or: code --install-extension ./vscode-markus
```

Then reload the window (`Developer: Reload Window`).

**Icon themes:** Markus does not replace your normal icons by default. To use the custom `.mks` icon in the explorer:

- **Preferences: File Icon Theme** → **Markus Icons**, or
- Set `"markus.fileIcons": true` in settings

### Live LaTeX preview

With a `.mks` file open, click the **preview** icon in the editor title bar.
It opens a PDF panel beside your source and recompiles ~1s after you stop typing.
Compile errors are shown in the panel with the offending line.

Settings:

- `markus.cliPath` — custom path to `markus` binary
- `markus.preview.debounceMs` — recompile delay (default `1000`)

